amdgpu: uvd_v4_2 — three Ghidra-derived fixes to Liverpool VCPU start (v76a)

v74 brought the Liverpool VCPU bring-up sequence to a state where the
register writes "look right" and the VCPU executes, but it times out
with a VM fault at page 0x300000 vmid 4. v75 enlarged the UVD BO from
~2.7 MB to 3.5 MB and the fault page did not change — eliminating BO
size as the variable.

A follow-up Ghidra session re-decompiled uvd_vcpu_start_baikal
(FUN_c88f8610), uvd_kmd_hw_init_stage2 (FUN_c88f8cf0), uvd_alloc_region
(FUN_c88f94e0), and uvd_ctx_dma_map_buffer (FUN_c88eb570) in the
Orbis 12.02 kernel, and identified three concrete mistakes in the v74
register sequence:

1) Spurious writes to 0x3d62 and 0x3d63 with a 0x44444444 pattern.
   Sony's uvd_vcpu_start_baikal NEVER writes these registers. The
   writes appear to have been misattributed from a sibling function
   (Gladius variant, possibly) during an earlier RE pass.

2) 0x3da9 page-size encoding missing. Sony computes the value as
   0x11010000 + log2(0x1000) + log2(0x100)*0x100 = 0x1101080c via a
   De-Bruijn log2 helper. We were writing 0x11010000, with the low
   12 bits (encoding 4 KB / 256 B page sizes) zeroed.

3) LMI_VM_VBASE was being written as fw_gpu_addr. Sony reads ctx[+0x88]
   and writes that — but uvd_kmd_hw_init_stage2 only initialises
   ctx+0x50/+0x70/+0x90 (the three region pointers); it never touches
   +0x88. The only function that writes +0x88 is uvd_ctx_set_field_88,
   called from uvd_ctx_dma_map_buffer, which in turn is only called
   from HDA audio code (hdac.c FUN_c88d7d50), not the UVD path.
   So Sony effectively writes VBASE = 0.

Full analysis: checkpoint/docs/research/2026-05-11-v75-uvd-result.md.

Expected hardware signals when this lands:
  ✅ if VBASE=0 was the key blocker: VCPU sets STATUS bit 1, ring test
     proceeds, OR a totally new error appears later in the pipeline.
  🟡 if the fault address moves: useful new data — we'd know the
     VCPU's hardcoded access depends on VBASE in some way.
  ❌ if same fault at page 0x300000: VBASE isn't the variable, and
     v76b (custom vmid 4 page-table population) becomes the next move.

Diagnostic prints retained from v74 — the timeout block now reports
"v76a: wrote 0" in place of "expected fw_gpu_addr" for clarity.

Signed-off-by: Meerzulee <mirzaali@screeninternational.org>

--- a/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/uvd_v4_2.c
+++ b/drivers/gpu/drm/amd/amdgpu/uvd_v4_2.c
@@ -536,12 +536,11 @@
 		uint32_t k = 4;

 		WREG32(0x3d3c, k);
-		WREG32(0x3d62,
-		       (k << 28) | k | (k << 4) | (k << 8) | (k << 12) |
-		       (k << 16) | (k << 20) | (k << 24));
-		WREG32(0x3d63,
-		       (k << 24) | (k << 20) | (k << 16) | (k << 12) |
-		       (k << 8) | (k << 4));
+		/* v76a: removed spurious 0x3d62/0x3d63 writes — Sony's
+		 * uvd_vcpu_start_baikal (FUN_c88f8610) decompilation has
+		 * no such writes. They appeared to come from a misread of
+		 * a sibling function and likely scribbled 0x44444444 into
+		 * unrelated VCPU configuration registers. */

 		/* Index/data sub-register 0x99 (VCPU CLK_CTRL). */
 		{
@@ -622,27 +621,39 @@
 	WREG32(0x3d98, RREG32(0x3d98) | 0x200);

 	/*
-	 * DMA register 0x3da9. Sony uses a pseudo-random pattern via
-	 * FUN_c88f6b70 (probably a hardware RNG read); we use the base
-	 * value Sony always ORs in. If DMA misbehaves we may need a
-	 * specific nonce here.
+	 * v76a: DMA register 0x3da9 — page-size geometry. Sony computes
+	 * this as 0x11010000 + log2(0x1000) + log2(0x100)*0x100 via a
+	 * De-Bruijn log2 helper (FUN_c88f6b70). 4 KB pages, 256 B sub-pages.
+	 * The low 12 bits are NOT optional — without them the DMA engine
+	 * has no idea of its page geometry.
 	 */
-	WREG32(0x3da9, 0x11010000);
+	WREG32(0x3da9, 0x11010000 | 12 | (8 << 8));    /* = 0x1101080c */
 	WREG32(0x3dab, 1);

 	/* GFX-side: enable UVD client bit at register 0x1401. */
 	WREG32(0x1401, RREG32(0x1401) | 8);

 	/*
-	 * ★ THE FIX ★ — write firmware GPU address into LMI_VM_VBASE.
-	 * Without these two writes the VCPU faults reading page 0x300800
-	 * (or 0x300600 depending on firmware version) on its first
-	 * instruction fetch because the LMI MMU has no mapping for the
-	 * VCPU's internal address space. This is the single most
-	 * important thing this function does vs mainline.
+	 * v76a: LMI_VM_VBASE — Sony's uvd_vcpu_start_baikal reads
+	 * ctx[+0x88] and writes it here, but ctx[+0x88] is never
+	 * initialised on the UVD path (uvd_kmd_hw_init_stage2 sets
+	 * region pointers at +0x50/+0x70/+0x90 but not +0x88; the only
+	 * function that writes +0x88 is uvd_ctx_set_field_88, called
+	 * from uvd_ctx_dma_map_buffer which is only ever called by the
+	 * HDA audio path). So Sony effectively writes VBASE = 0.
+	 *
+	 * v73/v74/v75 wrote fw_gpu_addr here on the assumption that the
+	 * VCPU needed to know where its firmware lives — but the cache
+	 * offset/size writes above (0x3d82..0x3d87) already give the
+	 * VCPU its memory layout. LMI_VM_VBASE appears to be something
+	 * else (a VM base for VCPU's own virtual-address space, possibly
+	 * 0 because the firmware operates on offsets from 0).
+	 *
+	 * If this is right, the VM fault at page 0x300000 vmid 4 should
+	 * either disappear or move to a different address.
 	 */
-	WREG32(0x3c69, lower_32_bits(fw_gpu_addr));    /* LMI_VM_VBASE_LO */
-	WREG32(0x3c68, upper_32_bits(fw_gpu_addr));    /* LMI_VM_VBASE_HI */
+	WREG32(0x3c69, 0);    /* LMI_VM_VBASE_LO = ctx[+0x88]_lo (= 0) */
+	WREG32(0x3c68, 0);    /* LMI_VM_VBASE_HI = ctx[+0x88]_hi (= 0) */

 	/* Clear DMA + soft-reset bit 0 — first stage of VCPU release. */
 	WREG32(0x3da5, 0);
@@ -713,7 +724,7 @@
 			  "LMI_STATUS=0x%08x\n",
 			  status, soft_reset, lmi_status);
 		DRM_ERROR("  LMI_VM_VBASE_HI=0x%08x LMI_VM_VBASE_LO=0x%08x "
-			  "(expected fw_gpu_addr=0x%llx)\n",
+			  "(v76a: wrote 0, fw_gpu_addr=0x%llx for ref)\n",
 			  vbase_hi, vbase_lo, fw_gpu_addr);
 		DRM_ERROR("  LMI_EXT40_ADDR=0x%08x\n", ext40_addr);
 		return -ETIMEDOUT;
